segments.text: Go ahead and start.
I am Mrs. Joe Blaisdell of Richmond, Texas, Fort Bend County.
I have lived here all of my life.
Mr. Blaisdell.
I'm Joe Blaisdell, Richmond, Texas, Fort Bend County.
And I've lived there practically all my life.
I was born in Indiana.
And I came to Texas with my folks when I couldn't quite carry my own bag.
In fact, I couldn't walk.
Okay, why did your folks come to Fort Bend County?
Well, I think more than anything else, my daddy wanted to move to a warmer climate.
All right, what did y'all do when you came here?
What did your dad do for a living?
A farmer.
A farmer.
And Ms. Blaser, what's your approach to this?
Well, my father was born in Harris County and moved here as a small child with his family.
And my mother came to Texas from Missouri when she was 10, and they were looking for warmer climate, I think.
My father was a building contractor.
was killed in that activity.
What year was this when they came here?
My mother is 83 today, and she was 12 years old.
Okay.
Could you tell me, you know, like some of the, do you remember some of the families here that when you were a child, the influential families loved?
Fort Bend County, Rosenberg, or Richmond.
I was born in Rosenberg.
Yes, ma'am.
And married and moved to Richmond in 31.
Okay.
You want to know about Richmond people?
Well, it doesn't matter.
Fort Bend County as a whole.
Just, you know, what you remember.
Well, up until the time I moved and married here, although the towns were so close, I did not know too many people here very well.
But the Moore family were politically and financially prominent.
Judge Moore and all of his sons.
The Bassett family was a family.
These are families that were here back in history.
They've been here a long time.
This was primarily agriculture and ranching at that time.
There's been a lot of industry come in since that time.
Do you remember any, for instance, floods or droughts or anything in particular?
Yes.
There was a terrible flood in 1913.
I don't remember too much of it except a lot of water, and we were in it.
When we were moving out, my people were farming at the time, and we moved out, and I remember the wagons and loaded with things in the water and the wheels.
That was 1913, and oh, off and on through the years, yes, we've had bad floods.
Joe was old enough probably to tell you something about the 1913 flood, were you, Joe?
Well, the 1913 flood was
It was the biggest flood that I've ever heard any of the old-timers ever talk about.
At that time, the water was all the way past Sugar Land.
You could go from here to Sugar Land in a boat.
What kind of bridge did they have across the river?
Was there a different bridge?
Well, the river bridge is the same bridge that was there in 1913.
But the wagon bridge was up above the railroad bridge about two blocks, three blocks.
And it was just a...
old steel framework bridge with a wooden floor in it.
Now was this, there was one I heard that was from Navasota that they brought down from Navasota, but it was washed out when they were driving some cattle.
Well, that bridge went down before we ever got here.
But I can remember after they built this second bridge there at the same location.
I remember back when they
Oh, some of these people that had farms and ranches south of town and across the river and so forth, that when they moved cattle, they wouldn't let them move but 10 head at a time across that bridge.
And cattle would get to trotting in that bridge and go swinging.
Yes, sir.
And shucks, there'd be lots of time getting maybe
Two, three hundred head or more of cattle across that bridge.
It took a lot of time, that ten-headed time.
What year did it fall in?
Ah, that last one fell in 1922, and that flood in 22.
We used to ferry that from then until about 26, wasn't it?
How'd they work the ferry?
Was it a...
It was a... Hand power.
Hand power?
had a cable and all they had was sort of a board and they were about two and a half feet long with blocks nailed on the end of it.
Two blocks where they'd line and go through it and they'd catch it.
What happened to it?
It got washed away or they just built a new bridge or what?
They built a new bridge on this side of the railroad bridge.
When did Highway 59 come through?
This bridge was built right there.
It was opened in 1925, this steel bridge down here.
The old bridge went in on 22 and then we rode the ferry from then on until we got the new bridge built.
The ferry was over by the 138th Street.
The road is in the same location going to Houston.
And originally, it was on the north side of the railroad track when they put the new bridge in, where they got it on the south side all the way through.
But there's about a mile out there that's on the north side of the track and then had to cross over.
And that was, oh, that road was a shell road way back when I was a little bit of kid.
That shell from Richmond, Houston.
Do you know anything about how Richmond got started?
You know, like Richmond-Rosenberg, the background of it?
Well, Richmond got started back, oh, 18-something.
That is according to the history of Fort Bend County.
People came from Galveston down to Mouth of the Brothers down here, and then come up the river and found this bend in the river.
And they liked the looks of it, so that's where they started the town.
Yes, they built the fort here.
I don't know whether you know it or not,
From that bridge over here to the WKM plant, it's only about a mile.
And the Brazos River is right behind that WKM plant.
But it makes this way long loop up there.
It's 10, 12 miles around the river that make that one mile across there.
Richmond got its charter at the same time Houston got theirs in the name of Harrisburg.
But they had visions of navigating the Brazos River.
But Houston got busy and worked up the ship channel, dug it out, and processed that.
So they grew and we didn't.
Nothing was done here.
Now, Santa Ana came through Richmond, right over here, didn't you?
Through this general area, I don't know just where.
Because I read somewhere like, you know, the Jane Long graveyard right over here.
Jane Long is in the Morton Cemetery.
The Morton Cemetery, that's right.
And didn't Santa, well, you know, I read somewhere that Santa came through there and he destroyed some of the graves, his soldiers.
That I couldn't tell you.
But that cemetery is something to see.
If you were to go through it and visit it,
the names in history that you know on the tombstones over there, Dex Smith.
Jane Long, where was her boarding house here?
You know where the coffee shop is.
It was right behind it.
In fact, it was only torn down.
Post Office Pharmacy.
This building, her boarding house was torn down about what, Joe?
What, five years ago?
I don't know.
I don't know, but I've always been under the impression that that boarding house was across the track, which burned down.
I can remember when it burned down.
It was an old two-story hotel building deal.
It was just across the railroad track right at the back of that drug store down there.
Well, now, this house that they tore down a few years ago was the one that was supposed to have been hers.
The one in the back of that old Mama Schiff's old home?
Right back of Post Office Pharmacy.
Well, that old Mama Schiff, that's where Jake Eichmann was raised.
Mama Schiff, who was she?
Well, she was an old Jewish rabbi's wife.
But this Jake Eichmann, all these Eichmann sporting goods stores in Houston,
Yes, sir.
And all over the state.
Mama Schiff was his aunt.
And they raised him right there.
He went to business in Richmond when he was a young man.
Okay, the Oshman's is here in Richmond now.
That doesn't have anything to do with the Oshman's Burning Goods, does it?
There's the Eichmanns over here now.
They're probably practically all of them some kind of kinfolk.
That's right.
That's right.
There were several families, but then they're all of them cousins or brothers or what have you.
Harry Robinson in there.
His wife is an Eichmann.
Robinson.
He runs that store.
Oh, OK.
Another question.
You've lived here all these years.
What changes have you seen, for instance, in the schools and the means of making a living, just general appearance of the town?
Well, building, I guess, is the biggest thing.
Ever since the war was over, there's been tremendous growth in the two towns.
And well, you can see how much it's grown since you came here just a little while.
There is some industry here now where for years we had no industry.
Gins and the cotton oil mill out here, and that was just about it.
We just didn't have any industry.
Could you tell me about the schools?
Lamar Consolidated was consolidated in what, 60?
No, no.

Lamar Consolidated was the independent districts of Rosenberg and Richmond, and then the rural areas that worked through the courthouse or through the state system went in with them within these boundaries sounded.
This was done by vote in 1947.
And I set up the first tax rolls in 1948.
I was their assessor and collector from 48 through 57.
And then retired from that.
And it showed tremendous growth in that period of time, but then it was, we thought it was, but it just doesn't compare at all to what's happened since then.
Well, has there been a period of
just stagnation like since the war, where it just, you know, just everything kind of leveled off for a while?
Are you talking about the economy, the school, or what?
Well, just general growth of the Fort Bend County Yards.
It's just been growing ever since the war.
It's been growing ever since.
And when I left the school, I went into the savings and loan business, where I had an opportunity to watch buildings.
And it just constantly grew.
And we kept thinking, well, it has to slow down.
But it didn't until just recently.
When did the Savings and Loans start?
What year was this?
The Gulf Coast started in 1958.
OK.
There was one at Rosenberg that got its charter in 1933.
Is that the Fort Bend?
Fort Bend Federal.
Fort Bend Federal.
OK. And another thing.
people coming into the community like, you know, like your Czechs and your Germans and what nationalities were here when y'all?
Well, I can remember when I knew everyone in Rosenberg and it was primarily German and Czech.
There were a few Mexicans and of course there were your Negroes.
There were not too many others.
There were a few English.
Dr. Yates' family, that group, but there was not many.
That was it.
Okay, and like... A few Jews, you know.
That would be the Oshmans and all of them, right?
Well, now, I'm talking about when I was coming along, and that would be... Oh, there were the Rosenzweigs and the Lipmans and... Well, the Oshmans weren't here then?
Yes, they weren't here.
They were in Richmond.
Okay, gotcha then.
You see, Richmond did not want the railroad.
Santa Fe.
The Santa Fe railroad.
They did not want all of that track and all of this, the hub for all these different areas.
So Rosenberg was selected as a site for this.
And it was named for a man named Rosenberg.
It was the Rosenberg Library in Galveston.
He was a financier.
He was a big man.
And he was instrumental in getting Rosenberg started.
That's why Rosenberg was started, because Richmond didn't want it.
Rosenberg started that, more or less, as a water stop on St. Pete.
All the locomotives were steamed then, and they had to get water.
There were nine men.
And they had a pump station there in Rodenburg for years until they wanted diesel.
Of course, they had two railroads together, Southern City and Santa Fe, and both used water from the same well and tank.
Okay, like, when did, uh, when, you know, like, modern facilities, like, when did y'all get city sewage and water and all this?
My uncle put in the first electric plant and ice plant in Richmond and Rosenberg in the early 20s, I guess.
Very early 20s.
I know I was just, it might have been before 20, was it, Joe?
Well, of course, they had an ice and light plant here.
But Rosenberg is.
And your uncle bought them out.
Well, but Rosenberg, he put that in.
That's the old Rosenberg light, was the light plant now.
The Houston Light and Power Company bought him out.
Okay.
Him and his partner, there were two of them.
Didn't he?
Now, where's that ice plant in Rosenberg I've seen by the U-Totem over there?
You know what I'm talking about?
Not by the U-Totem, but it's back there by Lane's Trading Post?
Right.
Back in there.
All right.
Is that the old plant that you're talking about?
Right.
Okay.
And he sold it to the Houston Light and Power Company.
It was before the 20s.
I was a little girl when they put electric lights in our house.
It was way before that.
I know it was before 1923, but I don't remember yet when it was built.
It was planned to come down here.
It was wild here.
The only time we had lights was at night.
They'd crank that generator up down there and run it at night and take time to shut it down.
We didn't get natural gas until about 26?
26, I think.
I think it was about 26.
In fact, it was almost 27.
Boy, it was 27 before they got
Got all the customers hooked up on fuel.
I'd say the electricity was shortly before the 1920s.
Gas about 1926.
And then they began, everybody had septic tanks, you know.
Then, I don't know just exactly when they did put the sewage in.
They had no sewage deal here.
They just run off.
Of course, that was before the bridges there.
Just run off.
Well, they just wanted to open the river right there.
Well, there was a building over there that burned right at this end of the bridge.
There used to be a water tower right there, and the sewage went right over the river right there at the back of it.
And that was just a sort of a get-by proposition for some people.
They didn't try to cover all the towns.
That in 1929 is when they started then to put this sewer business in, 2930 along there.
That's when they put sewers all over town here.
That's what was about to say.
All right.
Another question.
Do y'all remember anything real big that happened, for instance, like bank robberies, murders, or any big court cases of any type that was in Mr. Rosenberg?
Within our lifetimes, it was pretty settled.
Before that, it was rugged.
Well, I don't remember ever having a bank robbery handled here.
a couple of years ago when this camp was running out of motorcycles and they caught him out here before he got five miles from town.
Well, do y'all know, do y'all, have y'all ever heard of any of the famous outlaws, you know, like they came from Richmond-Rosenberg?
I mean, no, Richmond was a pretty rugged town when it first started.
I think it had more reputation than it actually, than was actually fact.
I think a lot of that was
Of course, it was rugged.
It had to be to survive.
I think a lot of its reputation came from your woodpeckers, you know, Jaybird's woodpeckers.
That's another thing to ask about the Jaybird and the woodpecker revolt.
Well, of course, that was before my time and his time.
Did y'all ever hear anything about it?
Jaybird then was in 1889.
That's when they had that shootout.
Didn't the governor had to send the state militia down here or something to break it up?
No.
I never read anything about it or heard anything about it.
Back when I was a little kid, of course, I was a Yankee.
But there used to be an old man here, old Major Davidson.
He was an old Confederate veteran.
And he took me to several different Confederate conventions.
And I just, oh, I was 10, 12 years old, I guess.
And I was shook.
So I played a lot of them old bugger talking, but I never did hear anybody say anything about them sending me.
state militia and things like that.
I don't know whether we even had state militia back in those days.
Well, it doesn't say anything about it in your Wharton's history of Fort Bend or any of those.
I haven't read of it.
The reason I said that is because I, you know, like in the book that I'm taking, Texas History Now, and I read somewhere in the book it said something about the Jaybird.
Jaybird and Whitpecker revolt.
And it said something like the governor, I forgot who the governor was during that period, but he sent
They called for him for help, and I think I heard he sent the state militia down here, or some men maybe, just some men to break it up.
Well, the fight was pretty much between the old timers right here, you know, that the coffee baggers came in and they were taking over the offices and running things.
Oh, several of them personally were in the know.
What was the policy of the Jaybirds and the Woodpeckers?
Was it like the Republicans and Democrats of nowadays, or would it be the Radicals?
Well, they had a problem there that went back to the Civil War.
You know, there's lots of people in Washington and in the northern states that
wanted to run on the Confederate States pretty rough when the war was over.
And they had some people here in the courthouse that seemed to be looking out for number one more than anything else.
And finally, my chief and local people got together and decided to move them out.
And they did.
Yeah, the old courthouse used to sit right where the city hall, right in the middle of that block where the city hall lived down there.
There, there in .
Before they built this new courthouse.
Okay.
And that was the courthouse in 1889 when they had the fight, and there was bullet holes around them walls in there.
One old skimp that I knew real well was just, well, I believe he was 14 years old.
And this house, well, it's right back post office.
On the highway there.
It's got a sort of a story and a half, and that was a Mack Farland home.
old man Earl, they called him old man Earl, he was 14 years old then.
And he ended up down one of them little dormer windows up there in the back of the house and shooting right in through the courthouse, right in through the door of the courthouse.
How many people were injured or killed in that thing?
Was it just blown out of proportion?
Well, the thing of it was, it was
some killings there.
Even before the fight here, there was killings in Wharton, Galveston, and all the people from around here.
The main thing here is when I was a kid, I'd say at least
Half or more than half of the people around here always wore pistols.
And they didn't wear it to be mean or tough or anything.
They just wore it, by golly, for protection.
And they didn't let anybody run over them.
And the only woodpecker that I remember lived right across the street here when I started school.
He was the only one that I ever knew of around here that people said was a woodpecker.
And he admitted it himself, but he wasn't involved in the fight at all.
He lived right across the street.
He ended up dying.
His daughter works down there for love now, that Miss Harris down there.
There's an old man booting his daughter.
Uh-huh.
Miss Harris.
Ms. Harris has got a daughter that teaches at the school.
Is that, what's her name?
She's an art teacher.
Is that the one?
I don't know.
Because there's the lady, there's the daughter, and then there's the mother that works at Love's.
No, the daughter doesn't have a daughter.
No, not the daughter, but the son did.
You know what I'm talking about?
There was no son.
The daughter.
Audrey Harris had only daughters.
And then she had, one of the daughters got married and the husband ran off, and she had a boy by her.
I was just wondering about that.
But another thing, when y'all were kids, what went on around here?
Like nowadays, we go to the show.
Most of the time, we go to Houston.
What did y'all do around here?
I did the same thing.
Went to Houston to shop.
Went to Houston during the week.
We'd go on Sunday afternoons to the movies or something like that.
Joe played baseball.
Yeah, but that was up 29, 30, along there.
Well, we played ball around here back when I was a little kid.
We didn't have anybody arrange any games or anything.
We just got together and chewed a little side and played ball.
Well, we had a lot of parties.
And church.
Everybody went to church more.
There was a lot of social life connected with your churches.
What was the main church here?
What was your main church in Richmond?
Baptist and Baptist.
There's the Tozer up there.
And Catholic?
I figured the Catholic would be because they always get checks.
Catholic church.
It was put in here.
Well, the Episcopal church, it wasn't there.
didn't have near the congregation that the Baptists had.
They had the money.
